Where's the rest of Eyes ?? OK, Half review, half request. The show is outstanding. 1983 is a really great year. I have grown to really love it. The boys just jam! goodness wow! this show is just great.  extremely clear, unlike the majority of gd shows that you can still download from archive.  the scarlet begonias>fire and eyes had me dancing in my seat at work. lol.

Best ScarletFire ever? I don't know if you can call any one ScarletFire the best but I think there is none better than 4-13-83.  It's not the most powerful.  It's not the longest. But there is no version second to this one.  Why?  Flawless.  Sure, Jerry flubs a line in Scarlet but that doesn't deter from the excellence of this performance.  ALL the jams build perfectly and crest and drop off like a perfect wave.  Someone earlier talked about how they go back and forth in the transition and then, BAM! perfect Fire.  The ending is also perhaps as good a Scarlet coda as you could ever hear.  Again, perfect timing.  Jerry is prominent in the mix and he is definitely driving the bus!  It's too bad that the time between the end of ScarletFire and the start of Estimate is cut.  Far more than noodling and tuning prior to the start, it's a sly bit of interplay that, again, BOOMS! into Estimate.  This may be the best estimate ever, as well.  Not the longest or most intense riffing but, again, the timing is impeccable and the jams build and crest perfectly.  After this, the rest of the show is merely ordinary excellence.  The beautiful beginning of the second set, second to none, rates five stars.  1983 was the golden age of ScarletFire and these versions are second to none.  Don't believe what someone else wrote.  The fall Scarletfre at the CEntrum was merely great.  This one is the shining star.

again how tasty yet another AUD that is stellar. Whats not to love?
I used to be a SBD only guy but then i was forced by fate to change my outlook somewhat and i must say fate has been kind!! :)Grab this show it's a sweet thing and I agree Brent was a force unto himself .

Where's the rest of Eyes? I wrote the previous review as I listened to the show, all happy and jamming along.  Then, in them middle of an absolutely large Eyes, it cut out about 8 minutes in.  What up?  Is it me?  It was like hitting a brick wall at 80 MPH.

I miss them terribly As I sit in my office playing santa, wrapping presents, jamming and sippin' a little chivas regal ( a gift from a friend) I am once again blown away by the boys.  The energy in the show reminds me of my first in 85 ( hampton) i started jammin on the dead in 83, i guess what freaks me out the most is how familiar every song is I've heard, it's like we heard it before we arrived on the planet, this show really digs down deep, it has the whole repetoire from ballads to country to jazzy jammin, scarlet/fire luv it I wish i was there but i'm here, short hair married 4 kids house in the berbs even church on sundays but i still crave those special moments when you can sit back listen with a new set of ears and enjoy some of the best musicians in our time, so my friends out there  I can honestly say I miss Brent Jerry the boys and all the cool heads that made the trips so cooool, take care merry christmas and don't forget to spread the love in the world today, i'm gonna listen to good luv one more time!!!!!!!!!!!!

Looking for a copy of this show for years Was at this 1983 show at the UVM gym that held 2K-3K people.  Everyone was pumped to be there.  Our friend's sister won a lottery for tickets and we came up from UMASS.  I got separated from my friends and I was able to move up real close.
Right after Scarlet/Fire was done I turned to so girl and said "Now I can die !!".  I also thought Estimated was great that night.
I have always been looking for this show and was willing to trade a Larry Bird autographed Dead ticket (Boston Garden) for a copy but now I have the show and still have the ticket.  Again, I can now die !!

My oh my... I may have to revise my rating system because of this show.  Have heard it a bunch of times over the last 20 years, and for some reason it never grabbed me. BING! Stunning Scarlet-Fire, and you can feel it was a magical night for the folks there.  It is wonderful to change, no?  This is surely the epitome of a 5-star dead show.  (I can't rate them ALL 5 stars, can I?...).  Great audience recording, magical night.

Beginning of a great year for me Drove up from NY with some HS buddies to this one, luckily we had friends that were freshmen at UVM so they had scored tickets.  They were only available to students.  I read elsewhere that Dan Healy held a class before the show on how to tape dead shows properly.  I was too busy tripping my face off to attend.  One of my favorite shows of all time.  They had to stack the PA on the floor in front of the stage.  Saw 6 or 7 more East Coast shows in 83, this was right up there as the best.

Throwing Stones this is an easy 5 star show crackling with energy and the quality of this aud is quite good. The jam in these earlier Throwing Stones are quite different than how they ended up later down the line, and this version just smokes. great show right out of the blocks.

just like being there I'm surprised so many folks raving about the great sound quality. It seems a little 'boomy' to me, bass heavy. Yet, that maybe gives one a better sense of 'being there.' Definitely brings back some powerful memories of tripping with the GD for me. Can almost feel the dose. Love the Throwing Stones jam.

What a first show! As I begin my 60th revolution around the sun, I still remember this show. The Morning Dew was transcendental. The Scarlet>Fire left burn marks on my soul. The Jack Straw opener left me with a grin bigger than that guy in the overalls in the front row of the movie. Needless to say, the bus came by and I got on....

Late to the party 60 turns around the sun before I got around to signing up and reviewing.  Listening from a distance of 40 years I see that objectively the early 80s with Brent were really great years musically, despite all the many challenges the band faced. The Jack Straw opener here is just an example of a 70s tune that had evolved into a musical epic.  Even if the 60s and 70s were other worldly the Brent years up till 86' were a musical peak in many ways.
